  "prompt": "What are some really good Korean spas in Minneapolis?",
  "response": "Okay, finding authentic Korean spas (jjimjilbang) in Minneapolis can be a bit tricky, as they're not as prevalent as in larger Korean communities.  However, I can give you some leads based on my research, reviews, and knowledge of the area. Keep in mind that offerings and quality can change, so it's always a good idea to call and confirm details before you go.\n\nHere's a breakdown of some places that are often mentioned, and what you might consider when choosing:\n\n**1.  Insadong Korean Sauna (Formerly known as The Golden Touch)**\n\n*   **Why it's often mentioned:** This is one of the most commonly cited options in the Minneapolis area. It seems to be a popular and accessible option with updated facilities.\n*   **What to expect:** Basic jjimjilbang experience with hot tubs, saunas, and relaxation areas. They have the option to book massages and other treatments.\n*   **Things to consider:** Reviews can be mixed regarding the authenticity of the service.\n*   **Location:** 6040 Nicollet Ave Minneapolis, MN 55419\n\n**What to consider when choosing:**\n\n*   **Authenticity:**  True jjimjilbangs offer a range of hot and cold pools, various types of saunas (like clay, salt, or jade saunas), communal scrub areas, and often a restaurant serving Korean food.  Some places might just be \"Korean-owned\" spas with some Korean treatments but not the full jjimjilbang experience.\n*   **Cleanliness:** Absolutely crucial. Check recent reviews specifically mentioning the cleanliness of the facilities (pools, saunas, locker rooms).\n*   **Services:**  Think about what you're looking for.  Are you primarily interested in the communal bathing, sauna experience, or are you looking for specialized treatments like Korean body scrubs (seshin)?\n*   **Cost:** Prices can vary widely depending on the length of stay and services chosen.\n*   **Atmosphere:**  Some spas are very busy and social, while others are more quiet and relaxing. Consider your preference.\n*   **Language Barrier:**  While most places will have staff who speak English, a bit of knowledge of basic Korean spa etiquette can be helpful.\n\n**Important Tips for Visiting a Korean Spa:**\n\n*   **Nudity:**  Be prepared for nudity in the gender-separated bathing areas. It's a standard part of the Korean spa experience.\n*   **Etiquette:**\n    *   Shower before entering the pools or saunas.\n    *   Keep your voice down in relaxation areas.\n    *   Don't bring phones into the wet areas.\n    *   Follow the instructions of the staff.\n*   **Hydration:** Drink plenty of water before, during, and after your visit.\n*   **Bring:** Comfortable clothes to change into after your spa experience. Most places provide towels and toiletries, but you might want to bring your own preferred products.\n\nGood luck finding the perfect Korean spa experience in Minneapolis! Remember to check recent reviews and call ahead to confirm details before you go.\n",
